    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-10-23T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-10-23T05:00:00-05:00" n="352"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d352">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/8291: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-10-23T18:00:00+08:00"
                            >October 23, 1936—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 23—9:40 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>512. Following from Nanking: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“October 23, 9 a.m. Bond<note n="43" xml:id="d352fn43">W. L. Bond, vice
                                president of the China National Aviation Corporation.</note> this
                            morning told me Bixby<note n="44" xml:id="d352fn44">H. M. Bixby,
                                president of China Airways Federal Incorporated, U. S. A., holding
                                company for the American interest in the China National Aviation
                                Corporation; also director of the latter.</note> is very
                            apprehensive that the Chinese military authorities may utilize planes of
                            the China National Aviation Corporation for military purposes thereby
                            affecting status of the American pilots. Such action might cripple the
                            activities of the corporation if hostilities were to begin. To protect
                            both the status of the American pilots and the American capital invested
                            in the corporation, Bond inquires on behalf of Bixby <pb facs="0459"
                                n="364" xml:id="pg_364"/> whether I would be authorized to make
                            informal oral request of the Chinese military authorities on behalf of
                            American interests involved that purely commercial character of the
                            corporation’s plane service be preserved in view of possible
                            eventualities.</p>
                        <p>I respectfully suggest I might speak informally to the Minister of War
                            and the Acting Minister of Communications. Please instruct by
                            telegraph.[”]</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>I informed Peck October 23, 9 a.m. that I approve action suggested in the last
                    paragraph of his telegram.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
